    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm running a linear regression on some housing price data but i'm running into an issue with my residuals. they aren't normally distributed at all—lots of skewness and some heavy tails. what's the best way to handle this so i don't mess up my inference?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Residuals not being normal, especially with skewness and heavy tails, is a classic problem. You can try a few things, but first, you should always check if your model assumptions are truly broken, or if it's just a small, noisy issue that a few extra datapoints can smooth over. A good data-wrangling approach is to try transforming the dependent variable, $Y$, before running the regression. Sometimes, a log transformation ($\\log(Y)$) or a square root transformation ($\\sqrt{Y}$) can pull those tails in closer to a bell curve.",
