    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i tried the log transform but the tails are still pretty beefy, almost like there are these weird outliers pulling the distribution away from center. is it better to just drop those points or should i look into a different type of model altogether, like maybe a robust regression or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Dropping points is tempting, but you're throwing away valuable data, and you don't want to lose the good stuff! It's a big mistake, unless those outliers are clearly data entry errors, which is rare when you're dealing with housing prices. Look at a robust regression first; that's your best bet for keeping the data while minimizing the influence of those heavy-tailed offenders.\n\nRobust regression methods, like M-estimators or RANSAC, are designed to be less sensitive to outliers. They don't let those few massive, weirdly priced houses completely skew your line. It's a good way to keep your linear structure while ignoring the noisy, overly enthusiastic data points. If you use a robust method, you can still get a decent estimate of the relationship, even if the underlying error distribution isn't perfectly Gaussian.",
      "source": "target",
