    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense. i'll check out the m-estimators then. one more thing, do you think there's any risk that these outliers are actually masking some kind of non-linear relationship that the linear model just can't see? like, if the errors are behaving that strangely, maybe there's a underlying pattern i'm missing entirely?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a sharp question, and you're thinking like a true data detective! Those heavy tails and skewness can absolutely be a sign that your linear assumption is just a clumsy approximation of something more complex. It's like trying to measure a mountain range with a straight ruler—you're going to get a rough sketch, but you'll miss the peaks entirely.\n\nIf the residuals are behaving this way, it might mean the relationship between your predictors and the price isn't truly linear. Instead of just throwing out the outliers or using a robust line, you should definitely explore non-linear models. Think about adding polynomial terms (like $X^2$ or $X^3$) to your linear model. That lets the line bend a little, giving you more flexibility to capture those hidden curves. Alternatively, you could look into generalized additive models (GAMs).",
      "source": "target",
